2015 my parents came over as I couldn’t fly down, 2016 and 2019 were fine. That’s half my flights home for Christmas since I’ve been living in the UK. 🤦🏻‍♀️

2017: A suspected hijacked plane made an emergency landing in Malta the day before my flight. All flights were being diverted to Sicily . Since I was the first flight out the following morning, my dad bought a Catamaran ticket to Sicily to meet me there. Thankfully it was fine.

2018: Dronegate at Gatwick. I was one of 100,000 people stranded at Gatwick Airport because someone decided to fly their drone. I had to get a train back to my flat and fly out 3 days later. I managed to find a seat just in time for Christmas day.

2020: All commercial flights to Malta cancelled, with mine moving from a Saturday to a Friday. Made it home but then I had to buy a £200 one way ticket back because my Ryanair flight got cancelled (all flights were, reparation only, which is what I had to buy)

2020 was suppose to be my year of travel. But at this point I do not see myself going anywhere that's not visiting my family before late 2021, or even 2022. Countries will still be there. I wish I could have gone to more places other than Malta/UK/France by 25 but oh well! (9/9)

As I see cases rise in Malta and across mainland Europe, I struggle to understand why people are travelling for a holiday during this time. This experience has confirmed that if I didn't have my family here I would not jump on a plane. Not worth it (8/9)

So far I've been to 2 restaurants. No matter how nice it is, it’s weird. I'm constantly looking around and I get agitated when someone's too close or not wearing a mask. After 4 months in isolation, adapting to a country where it's practically back to normal is HARD (7/9)

I sanitised my bag and luggage at the airport when I landed and again at home, before I shoved all my clothes in the washing machine and took a head to toe shower. I isolated for the first few days and went for a swab test. I stayed home until I got a negative result. (6/9)

We sat on the plan for an HOUR before we took off. Some passengers did not plan ahead for the forms and therefore had to sort them out at the gate. This was long and unnecessarily  stressful. The plane was packed. Why are people going on holiday? (5/9)

Everyone was socially distanced whilst boarding. Before I sat down I wiped the seat with a dettol wipe. When I settled in I changed my mask (has to be done every 4 hours) into a N95 mask and a homemade one over it. Not risking it with someone sitting next to me for 3 hours (4/9)

I wore a mask and avoided public transport to the airport. Once at the terminal, I kept away from people. Whilst I was there, Malta confirmed 14 new cases. I genuinely almost walked out of the departures and got an uber home. But I didn’t cos I really wanted to hug my mum. (3/9)

I spent the entire 4 months of lockdown home alone so I felt safe enough to travel, especially since Malta was down to 3 active cases. I bought a bum bag to put dettol wipes, antibacterial handwipes, hand san. All easily accessed. Filling in all the forms was stressful. (2/9)

So last weekend I flew over to Malta to visit my family and friends. I've not seen them in 8 months and if I'm being honest, I didn't want 2021 to be the next time I see them. Here's some thoughts on travelling during a pandemic if you're interested (1/9)

THERE WAS AN ALL LIVES MATTER PROTEST IN MALTA TODAY. Ashamed to be from that island.

Let’s follow in our ancestor’s footsteps. 4 innocent men died at the hand of the army after they were fighting for something important to them. 

Times sadly haven’t changed. But we can change it. Peaceful (and digital) protests shouldn’t include violence from either side. 5/5

How dare Maltese people fall silent now? How dare Maltese people speak AGAINST protesting? Protesting against our former oppressors & rising cost of living in 1919 was a need. Protesting against racism in 2020 is a need.  4/5

Rioting? How DARE. Protesting for basic human rights? HOW DARE. But Maltese people protesting the rising cost of bread? Needed.

How is protesting structural racism less of a necessity? Weren’t Maltese once oppressed and referred to as 2nd class citizens in their own country? 3/5

Lest we forget the sacrifices and courage our ancestors had to stand up to our oppressors (Malta was part of the British Empire). 

Maltese people literally have an annual public holiday to remind us of this day. Yet silence befalls too many about racism and recent events. 2/5

Today is Sette Gugno. It’s a public holiday in Malta in remembrance of the 7th June 1919 when British troops fired into a crowd of protesters killing 4 Maltese men. 

The Maltese were rallying against profiteering companies due to the rise in cost of living - such as bread. 1/5
